Demand Forecasting Using Time Series Modeling: Case Study

 

Background: In manufacturing sector, many decisions are taken based on forecasting future demand. The demand forecasting helps companies to manage accurate, timely and effective production. The sports goods manufacturing company identified 3 top products for which demand forecasting was most critical. The 5-years monthly sales data for 3 products was used to develop the model.

Objective: Forecast next 3 months sales using trend and seasonality exhibited over 5 years of sales data.

     

Import data and display first 6 rows

import os
import pandas as pd

os.chdir("D:/SANKHYA/Time Series Case Study/DATA")
salesdata = pd.read_csv('PRODUCT SALES DATA.csv')
salesdata.head(6)

Data Description

Analysis of Product 1

Create a time series object and visualize sales over 5 years

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

rng = pd.date_range('2014-01','2019-01',freq='M')

s1 = salesdata['Product1'].values[:60]
salesseries1 = pd.Series(s1, rng)

plt.plot(salesseries1);
plt.show()

The time series shows periodic peaks which indicates seasonality

 

Display ACF plot to check if product 1 sales forms stationary time series

from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf
plot_acf(salesseries1);
plt.show()

ACF plot shows a slow decay indicating non-stationarity

 

Dickey-Fuller test for product 1 time series

from arch.unitroot import ADF 
import warnings

warnings.filterwarnings("ignore") 

adf = ADF(salesseries1,lags=0,trend='nc')
adf.summary()
Augmented Dickey-Fuller Results
Test Statistic 0.798
P-value 0.885
Lags 0


Trend: No Trend
Critical Values: -2.60 (1%), -1.95 (5%), -1.61 (10%)
Null Hypothesis: The process contains a unit root.
Alternative Hypothesis: The process is weakly stationary.

Value of test statistic is greater than 5% critical value. Hence, Time series is non-stationary.

 

Dickey-Fuller test for 1st order differenced time series

from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.tools import diff
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore") 

salesdiff1 = diff(salesseries1)
(ADF(salesdiff1,lags=0,trend='nc')).summary()
Augmented Dickey-Fuller Results
Test Statistic -6.541
P-value 0.000
Lags 0


Trend: No Trend
Critical Values: -2.61 (1%), -1.95 (5%), -1.61 (10%)
Null Hypothesis: The process contains a unit root.
Alternative Hypothesis: The process is weakly stationary.

Value of test statistic is less than 5% critical value. Hence, Time series is stationary.

 

Automatic Model Identification and Parameter Estimation

Store auto.arima in object salesmodel1 and then get coefficients

import pmdarima as pm
salesseries1 = pd.to_numeric(salesseries1.astype(float))

salesmodel1 = pm.auto_arima(salesseries1,      
                      max_p=2, max_q=2,
                      max_P=2,max_Q=2,
                      d=1,m=12,         
                      seasonal=True,
                      D=1, suppress_warnings=True, 
                      trace=True)
